(ABSTRACT) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(This document defines how cyberspace protects itself. The model is) show newline
(simple: capabilities all the way down. Objects are content.) show newline
(Authorization flows through signed certificates. No labels, no ACLs, no) show newline
(ambient authority. You hold a capability or you don't.) show newline
() show newline
(We use the rigor of TCSEC B2 as a lens - particularly for covert channel) show newline
(analysis - but cyberspace is its own thing. This is our security) show newline
(architecture, in our language.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(THE MANIFESTO) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(    "Authorized capability set with auditing. No central authority.") show newline
() show newline
(You can have a central authority if you want one. That's up to you. But) show newline
(you don't need one. The architecture doesn't require it. Trust flows) show newline
(from keys you choose to trust, not from a hierarchy imposed upon you.) show newline
() show newline
(These principles were proven in VAXcluster security \(1984-1994\),) show newline
(proposed in SDSI at IETF 29 Seattle \(1994\), and implemented partially in) show newline
(products that didn't survive their parent companies. Cyberspace) show newline
(completes what was started.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
